# Line-ending policy.
#
# Default: Git auto-detects text vs binary on `add`, stores LF in the repo,
# and checks out the platform's native line ending. With `eol=lf` below
# we override the checkout side so shell scripts and pipe-delimited data
# files stay LF-only on Windows too — Git-Bash `IFS='|' read` otherwise
# leaves `\r` on the last field of each line, which silently breaks
# `verify-sidecars.sh` and `bundle-sidecars.sh` on Windows CI runners.
* text=auto

# Shell scripts must be LF on all platforms; a CRLF shebang is a
# classic "script won't run in Docker / on Linux" trap.
*.sh        text eol=lf
*.bash      text eol=lf

# PowerShell is LF-tolerant but also works with CRLF; let Windows devs
# have native endings if their editor prefers.
*.ps1       text

# Pipe-delimited data files the bash parsers read field-by-field. MUST
# stay LF so the last field doesn't gain a stray `\r`.
*.lock      text eol=lf

# Binary assets — never munge these.
*.png       binary
*.jpg       binary
*.jpeg      binary
*.gif       binary
*.ico       binary
*.icns      binary
*.pdf       binary
*.zip       binary
*.gz        binary
*.xz        binary
*.tar       binary
*.woff      binary
*.woff2     binary
